</table>
<p>The <b>Situationist International</b> (<b>SI</b>) was a small group of international political and artistic <a href="/wiki/Agitator" title="Agitator">agitators</a> with roots in <a href="/wiki/Marxism" title="Marxism">Marxism</a>, <a href="/wiki/Lettrism" title="Lettrism">Lettrism</a> and the early 20th century European artistic and political <a href="/wiki/Avant-garde" title="Avant-garde">avant-gardes</a>. Formed in 1957, the SI was active in Europe through the 1960s and aspired to major social and political transformations. In the 1960s it split into a number of different groups, including the Situationist Bauhaus, the Antinational and the <a href="/wiki/Second_Situationist_International" title="Second Situationist International">Second Situationist International</a>. The first SI disbanded in 1972.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> The Situationist International has also had a significant influence on <a href="/wiki/Anarchism" title="Anarchism">anarchism</a> since the 1970s.<sup class="noprint Template-Fact"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources&#160;since December 2008" style="white-space: nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed">citation needed</a></i>]</span></sup></p>
